{{Infobox MLA | name = Bob Wong | image = | imagesize = | caption = | office = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|Ontario MPP]] | term_start = 1987 | term_end = 1990 | predecessor = ''New riding'' | successor = [[Rosario Marchese]] | constituency = [[Fort York (electoral district)|Fort York]] | party = [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] | birth_name = Robert Charles Wong | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1941|04|27}} | birth_place = [[Fort Erie, Ontario|Fort Erie]], [[Ontario]] | residence = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] | occupation = Businessman | partner = }} '''Robert Charles Wong''' ({{zh|t=黃景培}}; born April 27, 1941) is a former [[politician]] in Ontario, [[Canada]]. He was a [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] from 1987 to 1990 who represented the [[Downtown Toronto|downtown]] [[Toronto]] riding of [[Fort York (electoral district)|Fort York]]. He served as a [[cabinet minister]] in the provincial government of [[David Peterson]].
==Background== Wong was educated at the [[University of Toronto]], [[York University]], [[Harvard University]], and the [[University of Waterloo]], earning [[Bachelor of Science]] and [[M.B.A.]] degrees. He was a special assistant of the [[Minister of National Health and Welfare (Canada)|Minister of National Health and Welfare]] from 1968 to 1970, and served as special advisor to Canada's first Minister of State for Multiculturalism in 1972. Wong later served as president of the Toronto District Liberal Association from 1974 to 1976, and of the Ontario Chinese Liberal Association in 1986. He also chaired the Toronto Ontario Olympic Committee, and was a member of the Multicultural Advisory Council.<ref name=icao>{{cite web |url=http://www.icao.on.ca/Institute/Leadership/Council/1019page1278.aspx |title=2010-2011 Members-at-Large Biographies |publisher=Institute of Chartered Accountants of Ontario |accessdate=2011-01-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105145331/http://www.icao.on.ca/Institute/Leadership/Council/1019page1278.aspx |archivedate=2010-11-05 |df= }}</ref>
In private life, served as chair of Goulding, Rose & Turner Ltd.,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pas.gov.on.ca/scripts/en/bios.asp?boardID=140156&persID=154554 |title=Public Appointments Secretariat, Ontario, Canada: Agency Members Biographies |publisher=www.pas.gov.on.ca |accessdate=2011-01-11}}</ref> and was a director of May Mikkila Inc., Abico Management Ltd., Multilingual Television Ltd., Channel 47 Toronto (Canada's first multilingual television station)<ref name=icao/> and Sky Continental Management Inc. He established the first brokerage office in Toronto's Chinatown, and was named Analyst of the year for 1980 by Financial Times of Canada. He also is the author of "Computing: An Introduction" and the co-author of "Algorithms", both published in 1967.
==Politics== He was elected to the Ontario legislature in the [[Ontario general election, 1987|1987 provincial election]], defeating [[Joe Pantalone]] of the [[New Democratic Party of Ontario|New Democratic Party]] (NDP) by 137 votes in the downtown Toronto riding of [[Fort York (electoral district)|Fort York]].<ref name="1987 results">{{cite news |title=Results from individual ridings |newspaper=The Windsor Star |date=September 11, 1987 |page=F2}}</ref> He was appointed to cabinet on September 29, 1987 as [[Minister of Energy (Ontario)|Minister of Energy]].<ref name="1987PetCab">{{cite news |title=Wrye gets new cabinet job |newspaper=The Windsor Star |date=September 29, 1987 |page=A1}}</ref> He was named [[Ministry of Citizenship and Immigration (Ontario)|Minister of Citizenship]] responsible for race relations, multiculturalism and [[Ontario Human Rights Commission]] on August 2, 1989.<ref name="1989PetCab">{{cite news |title=Veterans bear load as 8 ministers cut in Peterson shuffle |last=Allen |first=Gene |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=August 3, 1989 |page=A1}}</ref>
The Liberals were defeated by the NDP in the [[Ontario general election, 1990|1990 provincial election]], and Wong lost the Fort York riding by about 1,500 votes to [[Rosario Marchese]].<ref name="1990 results">{{cite news |title=Ontario election: Riding-by-riding voting results |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=September 7, 1990 |page=A12}}</ref> He sought to return to the legislature in the [[Ontario general election, 1995|1995 election]], but lost again to Marchese by over 2,000 votes.<ref name="1995 Election Results">{{cite web |url=http://results.elections.on.ca/results/1995_results/valid_votes.jsp?e_code=36&rec=0&district=fort+york&flag=E&layout=G |title=Summary of Valid Ballots by Candidate |publisher=Elections Ontario |date=June 8, 1995 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223210723/http://results.elections.on.ca/results/1995_results/valid_votes.jsp?e_code=36&rec=0&district=fort+york&flag=E&layout=G |archivedate=February 23, 2015 |df= }}</ref>
Wong supported [[Gerard Kennedy]] for the leadership of the Ontario Liberal Party in 1996.
===Cabinet positions=== {{s-start}} {{Canadian cabinet member navigational box header |ministry=David_Peterson}} {{ministry box cabinet posts | post2preceded = [[Gerry Phillips]] | post2 = [[Ministry of Citizenship and Immigration (Ontario)|Minister of Citizenship]] | post2years = 1989–1990 | post2note = also Responsible for Race Relations and Ontario Human Rights Commission | post2followed = [[Elaine Ziemba]]
| post1preceded = [[Vince Kerrio]] | post1 = [[Ministry of Energy (Ontario)|Minister of Energy]] | post1years = 1987–1989 | post1note = | post1followed = [[Lyn McLeod]]
}} {{s-end}}
==Later life== Wong was later appointed chair of the [[Canadian Automobile Association]] (CAA) Ontario's Government and Public Affairs Committee.<ref name=icao/> He is now Vice-Chairman of Leon Frazer & Associates Ltd,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leonfrazer.com/ourteam.asp#robertwong |title=Leon Frazer & Associates Investment Counsel |publisher=www.leonfrazer.com |accessdate=2011-01-11 }}</ref> and is a board member of the [[Royal Ontario Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rom.on.ca/about/leaders/campaign.php |title=ROM Leadership |publisher=Royal Ontario Museum |accessdate=2011-01-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128134317/http://rom.on.ca/about/leaders/campaign.php |archivedate=2010-11-28 |df= }}</ref>
