{{Infobox software | name = Mozilla Sunbird | logo = SunbirdIcon.png | screenshot = Mozilla Sunbird.png | caption = Mozilla Sunbird main window running under [[Windows Vista]] | developer = [[Mozilla Foundation]] and community | released = 1.0 Beta1 | programming language = [[C++]], [[XUL]], [[XBL]], [[JavaScript]] | operating system = [[Windows]], [[Linux]], [[BSD UNIX]], [[macOS|OS X]], [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris]], [[OpenSolaris]] and [[OS/2]] | language = [[Multilingual]],{{which|date=February 2015}}<ref name="Sunbird - International Downloads">{{cite web | title = Sunbird - International Downloads | publisher = mozilla.org | url = https://www.mozilla.org/projects/calendar/sunbird/l10n_download.html | accessdate = 2007-06-12 }}</ref> EULA in English only<ref name=mozeula>{{cite web | url = https://www.mozilla.org/legal/eula | title = Mozilla Sunbird End-User Software Licensing Agreement | accessdate = 2007-06-12 | publisher = mozilla.org}}</ref> | genre = [[Personal information manager]] | license = [[Mozilla Public License|MPL]] 1.1, MPL 1.1/[[GNU General Public License|GNU GPL]]/[[GNU LGPL]] tri-license | website = {{url|https://www.mozilla.org/en-US/projects/calendar/}} }} '''Mozilla Sunbird''' is a discontinued [[free and open-source software|free and open-source]], [[cross-platform]] [[calendaring software|calendar application]] that was developed by the [[Mozilla Foundation]], [[Sun Microsystems]] and many volunteers.<ref name="volunteerlist">[https://www.mozilla.org/credits/ Mozilla contributors list], ''Mozilla.org''</ref> Mozilla Sunbird was described as "...&nbsp;a cross platform standalone calendar application based on Mozilla's [[XUL]] user interface language."<ref name="mainsunbirdpage">[https://www.mozilla.org/projects/calendar/sunbird/index.html The Sunbird Project - Standalone Calendar] - Main project page describing the project.</ref> Announced in July 2003,<ref name="sunbirdAnnounced">[http://www.mozillazine.org/talkback.html?article=3432 Mozilla Sunbird Standalone Calendar Project Launches - MozillaZine Talkback] - MozillaZine article announcing the Sunbird Project</ref> Sunbird was a standalone version of the [[Mozilla Calendar Project]].
It was developed as a standalone version of the [[Lightning (software)|Lightning]] calendar and scheduling extension for the [[Mozilla Thunderbird]] and [[SeaMonkey]] mail clients. Development of Sunbird was ended with release 1.0 beta 1 to focus on development of [[Lightning (software)|Mozilla Lightning]].<ref>[https://www.mozilla.org/projects/calendar/releases/sunbird1.0b1.html Sunbird 1.0 beta1 Release Notes]: "This is the last public Sunbird release by the Calendar Project." . Retrieved 2010-04-01.</ref><ref>[http://weblogs.mozillazine.org/calendar/2009/02/calendar_project_at_a_critical.html Calendar Project at a critical juncture] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126024401/http://weblogs.mozillazine.org/calendar/2009/02/calendar_project_at_a_critical.html |date=2010-01-26 }}, Calendar Weblog. Retrieved 2010-04-01.</ref> {{As of|2017}}, the “latest development version” of Sunbird was still 1.0b1 from January 2010, and no later version has been announced. Unlike Lightning, Sunbird does not receive updates to its time zones database anymore.
==Sun contributions== Sun Microsystems contributed significantly to the Lightning extension project to provide users with a free and open-source alternative to [[Microsoft Office]] by combining [[OpenOffice.org]] and Thunderbird/Lightning.<ref>{{cite web |last=Paquet |first=Simon |url=http://weblogs.mozillazine.org/calendar/2006/10/sun_microsystems_announces_int.html |title=Calendar Weblog |publisher=Weblogs.mozillazine.org |date=2006-10-05 |accessdate=2010-04-07 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212170048/http://weblogs.mozillazine.org/calendar/2006/10/sun_microsystems_announces_int.html |archivedate=2010-02-12 |df= }}</ref> Sun's key focus areas in addition to general bug fixing were calendar views, team/collaboration features and support for the [[Sun Java System Calendar Server]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.openoffice.org/editorial/mozilla_lightning_and_OOo.html |title=Interview On Mozilla Lighting and |publisher=Openoffice.org |date= |accessdate=2010-04-07}}</ref> Since both projects share the same code base, any contribution to one of them is a direct contribution to the other.
==Trademark issues and Iceowl== {{Main|Mozilla Corporation software rebranded by the Debian project}} Although it is released under a [[Mozilla Public License|MPL]], MPL/[[GNU General Public License|GPL]]/[[LGPL]] tri-license, there are trademark restrictions in place on Mozilla Sunbird which prevent the distribution of modified versions with the Mozilla branding.
As a result, the [[Debian]] project created [[Iceowl]], a virtually identical version without the branding restrictions.
